  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Sets international standards for combating money laundering\n- Provides guidelines for financial institutions and governments\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigation and prosecution\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines\n- Provides frameworks for preventing financial crimes\n- Offers technical assistance to countries\n\n4. Bank Secrecy Act (US) and similar national laws\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Help track and prevent money laundering\n\n5. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Establishes global banking standards\n- Includes regulations to prevent financial crimes\n\nMost countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, requiring banks and financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report large or suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained money as legitimate income.",
